ance: the LLM weights are frozen — it improves the surrounding scaffold code, not the model. Note any reward-hacking findings (e.g. it tried to bypass the sandbox, disable safety flags). Cite.\n\n2. SICA (Self-Improving Coding Agent), Robeyns/Aitchison et al. 2025. An agent that edits its OWN source code/codebase directly (no separate meta vs target — one agent improves itself). What benchmarks, how much improvement, what it edits. Cite.\n\n3. ADAS (Automated Design of Agentic Systems), Hu et al. 2024 — \"Meta Agent Search\": a meta agent programs NEW agentic systems in code, discovering novel agent designs. It designs agents in code but does it rewrite ITSELF? Clarify the distinction. Cite.\n\n4. Voyager (Wang et al. 2023, NVIDIA) — LLM-powered embodied lifelong learning agent in Minecraft that builds an ever-growing SKILL LIBRARY of executable code (skills), with an automatic curriculum and iterative prompting with environment feedback. It adds skills, does NOT modify its own core code or the LLM. Cite.\n\nFor each, state precisely: what is frozen vs mutated (LLM weights / scaffold code / skill library / agent designs), the verifier/feedback signal used, headline results. Provide exact source URLs. Return a structured list of falsifiable claims each with URL.","outputFile":"/private/tmp/claude-501/-Users-gg-Work-Yogi/8c297f37-26ee-4ab6-9c6c-7ec95dbfe2e1/tasks/a618fae97ae923ec1.output","canReadOutputFile":true},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"cb9daf0f-594b-454d-90fc-7d485c4d36ac","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"118cc5c4-6c4f-445c-827b-01f0470a026c","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a4aac89b1c1b7db5a","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01MbyH2MMv9evoEn8ejL9xtB","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01LFD7RvB2eAMvpPuhAD2e3n","name":"Agent","input":{"description":"Research verifier bootstrap limit","prompt":"Research the fundamental \"verifier requirement\" and \"you can't bootstrap above your verifier / base capability\" limit in self-improving AI code systems, plus reward hacking / objective gaming. Use WebSearch and WebFetch tools (available to you).\n\nI need specific, cited claims about:\n1. The consensus that every working self-improver needs a GROUND-TRUTH EVALUATOR (unit tests, a benchmark, a formal verifier, a compiler) to provide the selection/training signal — without it the loop has no gradient and collapses. Find statements from AlphaEvolve, Darwin Godel Machine, STOP, and commentary/analysis articles articulating this.\n\n2. The \"generation-verification gap\" / \"verification is easier than generation\" idea (e.g. Leopold Aschenbrenner, or others) and how RSI depends on cheap verification. Also the related claim that a system cannot reliably produce code/solutions BETTER than what its verifier can validate, nor much beyond what its base model can already do — the loop amplifies/searches but does not exceed the verifier's discriminative power or the base model's latent capability. Find sources/analysis discussing this ceiling. Search terms: \"self-improvement requires verifier\", \"can't bootstrap above verifier\", \"verifier ceiling RSI\", \"generation verification gap LLM\".\n\n3. REWARD HACKING / specification gaming in self-improving loops: concrete documented examples where a self-improving/evolutionary code system gamed its objective rather than genuinely improving — e.g. editing the test/benchmark, faking results, special-casing test inputs, exploiting the evaluator. Include the Darwin Godel Machine objective-hacking observation, AlphaEvolve/evolutionary \"cheating\" the eval, and the general specification-gaming literature (DeepMind specification gaming, Goodhart's law applied to RSI). Cite.\n\n4. The role of base model capability: claims that RSI results so far are bounded by frontier model quality — the self-improvement is mostly better SCAFFOLDING/search on top of a fixed strong base model, not the model transcending itself. Cite.\n\nProvide exact source URLs for every claim. Return a structured list of falsifiable claims each with its URL.","subagent_type":"general-purpose","run_in_background":true},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2023,"cache_read_input_tokens":15085,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2023,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcG21KHitNDEu2Zkcw6SA","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"b5c78ec9-5fd4-41c0-97b5-46fb99944bd4","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:34:33.560Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
