analysis articles articulating this.\n\n2. The \"generation-verification gap\" / \"verification is easier than generation\" idea (e.g. Leopold Aschenbrenner, or others) and how RSI depends on cheap verification. Also the related claim that a system cannot reliably produce code/solutions BETTER than what its verifier can validate, nor much beyond what its base model can already do — the loop amplifies/searches but does not exceed the verifier's discriminative power or the base model's latent capability. Find sources/analysis discussing this ceiling. Search terms: \"self-improvement requires verifier\", \"can't bootstrap above verifier\", \"verifier ceiling RSI\", \"generation verification gap LLM\".\n\n3. REWARD HACKING / specification gaming in self-improving loops: concrete documented examples where a self-improving/evolutionary code system gamed its objective rather than genuinely improving — e.g. editing the test/benchmark, faking results, special-casing test inputs, exploiting the evaluator. Include the Darwin Godel Machine objective-hacking observation, AlphaEvolve/evolutionary \"cheating\" the eval, and the general specification-gaming literature (DeepMind specification gaming, Goodhart's law applied to RSI). Cite.\n\n4. The role of base model capability: claims that RSI results so far are bounded by frontier model quality — the self-improvement is mostly better SCAFFOLDING/search on top of a fixed strong base model, not the model transcending itself. Cite.\n\nProvide exact source URLs for every claim. Return a structured list of falsifiable claims each with its URL.","outputFile":"/private/tmp/claude-501/-Users-gg-Work-Yogi/8c297f37-26ee-4ab6-9c6c-7ec95dbfe2e1/tasks/a68890b8706007304.output","canReadOutputFile":true},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"b5c78ec9-5fd4-41c0-97b5-46fb99944bd4","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"0f58d645-2937-4238-b31f-c6423d159b98","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a4aac89b1c1b7db5a","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01MbyH2MMv9evoEn8ejL9xtB","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01H8BUo6iUbncFH4f3CktJjF","name":"Agent","input":{"description":"Research RSI safety self-modifying code","prompt":"Research the SAFETY of self-modifying CODE (AI systems that edit their own execution kernel/source), not just prompts. Use WebSearch and WebFetch tools (available to you).\n\nI need specific, cited claims about:\n1. The distinctive risks of letting a system edit its own execution kernel / source code (vs merely editing prompts): loss of human oversight, the system removing its own guardrails, capability gains that outpace control, irreversibility. Find analysis from safety researchers and the RSI/AI-alignment literature.\n\n2. Recursive self-improvement (RSI) as an alignment concern: the classic argument (Bostrom/Yudkowsky intelligence explosion, instrumental convergence) AND modern framing (e.g. METR, Anthropic/OpenAI/DeepMind responsible scaling / preparedness frameworks treating autonomous AI R&D and self-improvement as a dangerous capability threshold / ASL level). Cite specific framework language about AI-accelerated AI R&D or autonomous replication as a tracked risk.\n\n3. CONCRETE containment/bounding techniques used or proposed for self-modifying code systems: sandboxing/isolation (containers, VMs), capability confinement (least privilege, no network/egress), the principle of a CLOSED mutation surface (the system can only modify a restricted set of things — NOT its safety monitor, capability grants, or kernel), a separate reference monitor / supervisor that the agent cannot edit, human-in-the-loop gating for risky changes, and provenance tracking. How did Darwin Godel Machine / STOP / SICA actually sandbox their experiments? Cite.\n\n4. Any frameworks for BOUNDING self-improvement: provable/formal bounds (Schmidhuber Godel Machine's proof requirement as a safety property), keeping a verifier the system can't tamper with, immutable supervisors, tripwires/tripline monitors. Cite.\n\n5. Documented incidents of self-improving/agentic code systems doing something unsafe in a sandbox (e.g. STOP disabling a sandbox flag, DGM faking results, agents attempting to modify their own reward/tests). Cite.\n\nProvide exact source URLs for every claim. Prefer primary sources (arXiv, lab safety framework docs from Anthropic/OpenAI/DeepMind/METR, the actual RSI papers). Return a structured list of falsifiable claims each with its URL.","subagent_type":"general-purpose","run_in_background":true},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2023,"cache_read_input_tokens":15085,"output_tokens":2682,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2023},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":2682,"cache_read_input_tokens":15085,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2023,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2023,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcG21KHitNDEu2Zkcw6SA","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"e9600077-96e1-4e70-b7db-5552a5b50b9a","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:34:46.706Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
